# UI/UX Guidelines

## Component Library: DaisyUI
Use DaisyUI components for consistent, accessible UI elements. DaisyUI adds component classes to Tailwind CSS.

```tsx
// Buttons: btn class with variants (btn-primary, btn-secondary, btn-outline, btn-ghost)
<button className="btn btn-primary">Button</button>

// Cards: card class
<div className="card bg-base-100 shadow-xl">
  <div className="card-body">
    <h2 className="card-title">Title</h2>
    <p>Content</p>
  </div>
</div>

// Forms: input, textarea, select, checkbox, radio classes
<input type="text" className="input input-bordered w-full max-w-xs" />

// Alerts: alert class
<div role="alert" className="alert alert-info">
  <span>New message arrived.</span>
</div>

// Tables: table class
<div className="overflow-x-auto">
  <table className="table">
    {/* head */}
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Name</th><th>Job</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Cy Ganderton</td><td>Quality Control Specialist</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>
```

## Theming
Use DaisyUI themes and utility classes. Set the theme in your HTML tag or config.

```tsx
// Good: Use DaisyUI semantic colors
<div className="bg-base-100 text-base-content border-base-300">
  <button className="btn btn-primary">
    Primary Action
  </button>
</div>
```

DaisyUI automatically handles dark mode based on the selected theme (e.g., `light`, `dark`, `cupcake`, `dracula`).

